            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Symptom: Water backs up in sink when disposal runs, drains slowly even with disposal operating, or disposal grinds normally but water doesn't drain. Common causes: Clogged drain line downstream of disposal (most common), improperly vented drain causing air lock, disposal outlet clogged with accumulated waste, or P-trap clog. DIY troubleshooting: Run disposal with hot water (sometimes clears minor soft clogs), check P-trap for clogs (place bucket underneath, loosen slip-joint nuts, clean trap), verify proper drain line slope (should angle downward toward main drain—sagging pipes create low spots where waste accumulates), check air gap or high loop on dishwasher drain (prevents dishwasher water from backing into disposal but can become clogged), and verify disposal outlet isn't clogged with accumulated waste. When to call professional: Water backs up into both sink bowls (indicates main drain clog requiring professional [link:/services/drain-clearing|drain clearing]), persistent slow drainage despite clearing visible clogs, gurgling sounds from drain during disposal operation (venting problem), or sewage odors from drain (indicates drainage or venting issues). Prevention: Run disposal with adequate water (poor water flow allows waste to accumulate in drain rather than flushing completely), avoid putting grease down disposal (major cause of drain clogs), monthly disposal cleaning prevents accumulation, and annual drain maintenance including main line inspection prevents major clogs. Likely outcomes: Simple P-trap cleaning resolves drainage issues $0 (DIY) or $85-$125 (professional service call), drain line cleaning $125-$245 for straightforward clogs, main drain line clearing $195-$450 depending on clog location and severity, and drain line replacement if damaged by corrosion $450-$950."
