            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "The mistake: Running hot or warm water during disposal operation instead of cold water. Why it's harmful: Hot water melts fats and grease in food waste, melted fats flow through disposal into cooler drain pipes where they re-solidify coating pipe walls, accumulated grease narrows drain diameter eventually causing complete blockage, and grease clogs are among most difficult and expensive to clear. Damage caused: Gradual drain line restriction from grease buildup, eventual complete drain blockage requiring professional [link:/services/drain-clearing|clearing] ($195-$450), and potential damage to main sewer line from grease accumulation ($500-$1,500 repair). Correct procedure: Always use cold water during grinding (keeps grease solid for grinding and flushing), run cold water 15-20 seconds after grinding (ensures complete flushing), save hot water for after disposal use (you can run hot water after disposal operation completes), and avoid putting excessive grease down disposal regardless of water temperature. Common misunderstanding: Some people assume hot water 'helps dissolve' food waste—this is incorrect and counterproductive. Cold water keeps everything solid for proper grinding and prevents grease problems downstream. If you've been using hot water: If you've routinely used hot water, your drain lines likely have grease accumulation. Schedule professional drain inspection and cleaning ($125-$245) before complete blockage occurs—preventive cleaning costs less than emergency clearing."
